article.description: The fifth-seeded Utes erased a 15-point deficit, this time in the first half, and went on to rout No. 4 seed Arizona State 86-65 in the second round of the NCAA Tournament.
article.headline: Utah rallies from 15 down to beat Sun Devils
article.linkText: Utah rallies from 15 down to beat Sun Devils
article.story:
TUCSON, Ariz. -- Fifteen-point deficits are nothing to Utah.

The fifth-seeded Utes erased another one, this time in the first half, and went on to rout No. 4 seed Arizona State 86-65 on Monday night in the second round of the NCAA Tournament.

Kim Smith, four-time Mountain West Conference player of the year, had 25 points and nine rebounds and Utah (26-6) won its sixth in a row to advance to the round of 16 for the second time in school history.

The Utes, who rallied from 15 down in the second half to beat Middle Tennessee in the first round, travel to Albuquerque for a Saturday matchup against the winner of the Tuesday night game against No. 1 seed Ohio State and Boston College.

"It's just a testament to our team," Smith said. "We just keep on believing in ourselves and we just keep on battling back."

Amy Denson scored 14, Emily Westerberg 12 and Kristen Kovesdy 11 for the Sun Devils (25-7), who failed to repeat last season's regional semifinal appearance.

Shona Thorburn added 24 points and 11 rebounds, and Julie Larsen scored 19 for the Utes, winners of the Mountain West Conference tournament.

Utah outscored Arizona State 34-13 over the last 10 minutes on a night that looked grim for the Utes after the Sun Devils opened a 34-19 lead.

"Arizona State started, obviously, very quickly," Utah coach Elaine Elliott said, "and it sort of looked like they were going to make a statement."

During a timeout, Elliott said, "We were talking about just trying to be closer at halftime and try to put a better second-half together."

Closer, indeed. The Utes scored the last 15 points of the half to make the score 34-34 at the break.

"We came out just excited to play," said Kovesdy, a senior playing her final ASU game. "We should have sustained that the whole game."

Smith started the outburst with a 3-pointer. She and Larsen scored five apiece in the run. Thorburn sank a jumper to cut it to 34-33 with 34 seconds left. She had a chance to give the Utes the lead after being fouled with two seconds to go in the half. She made the first free throw to tie it but missed the second.

Utah's scoring streak reached 19-0 when Perry and Smith made the first two baskets of the second half to go up 38-34. The Utes went ahead 47-40 on Thorburn's uncontested driving layup with 10:34 to play.

Arizona State tied it at 52 when Kovesdy made two free throws with 8:50 to go.

But Utah scored the next six, four by Larsen, to trigger an 18-5 run. Larsen's' 3-pointer made it 70-57 with 4:18 left.

"When we had lapses on defense, which were more than we normally have, they did a great job of stepping up and hitting shots," Arizona State coch Charlie Turner Thorne said.

The Utes shot 59 percent in the second half (17-for-29), including 4-of-5 3-pointers. After shooing 54 percent in the first half, the Sun Devils managed just 30 percent in the second (9-of-30).

"I don't know that we would've beat anybody tonight," Turner Thorne said.

Arizona State, playing a two-hour drive from its Tempe campus, scored the first seven points of the game and was up 13-2 after Kirsten Thompson's inside basket. The Utes cut it to 17-13 on Smith's inside basket with 11:44 left in the half.

But Danielle Orsillo's 3-pointer kicked off a 17-6 Arizona State run and the Sun Devils led 34-17 on Kovesdy's 3-pointer 6:44 before the break. The Sun Devils didn't score again in the half.

Utah freshman Morgan Warburton played the game wearing a special mouth guard and some of her front teeth wired together after taking a smack to the face in the Utes' first-round victory over Middle Tennessee.
